(2698, 131, '_elementor_data', '[{"id":"rdigcme","elType":"section","settings":[],"elements":[{"id":"hfcqhhe","elType":"column","settings":{"_inline_size":"","_column_size":100},"elements":[{"id":"eeu7sa9","elType":"widget","settings":{"editor":"<h3><strong>The three layers model of the Cognitive Radio<\\/strong><\\/h3>"},"elements":[],"widgetType":"text-editor"}],"isInner":false}],"isInner":false},{"id":"kzpyltm","elType":"section","settings":[],"elements":[{"id":"klvwfvs","elType":"column","settings":{"_inline_size":"","_column_size":100},"elements":[{"id":"2uth6tr","elType":"widget","settings":{"image":{"url":"http:\\/\\/localhost\\/wordpress\\/wp-content\\/uploads\\/2017\\/05\\/SmartSensors1-1.png","id":589},"caption":"Fig. 1","image_box_shadow_box_shadow_type":"yes"},"elements":[],"widgetType":"image"}],"isInner":false}],"isInner":false},{"id":"qs32ndb","elType":"section","settings":[],"elements":[{"id":"bkhpech","elType":"column","settings":{"_inline_size":"","_column_size":100},"elements":[{"id":"7ylqzsd","elType":"widget","settings":{"editor":"<h3><strong>To explain this model, we cut the model of Figure 1. into three main layers<\\/strong><\\/h3><ul><li>A <a href=\\"http:\\/\\/www.rennes.supelec.fr\\/ren\\/rd\\/scee\\/themes\\/scee_ti.html\\">high level layer<\\/a>, which contains primarily the application layer and man-machine type interfaces, called higher layer;<\\/li><li><a href=\\"http:\\/\\/www.rennes.supelec.fr\\/ren\\/rd\\/scee\\/themes\\/scee_capteurs-intermediaires.html\\">An intermediate layer<\\/a> containing transport and network layers;<\\/li><li>A <a href=\\"http:\\/\\/www.rennes.supelec.fr\\/ren\\/rd\\/scee\\/themes\\/scee_freq.html\\">low level layer<\\/a>, which contains MAC and physical layers, called the lower layer.The set of these layers runs on a SR platform (possibly ideal), but this model also runs on a software defined radio platform . These software radio platforms are based on hardware architecture of execution, which in general is heterogeneous. This platform is ideally hidden via an abstraction layer that offers a transparency in terms of implementation of software components to process the signals.<\\/li><li>We further illustrate the model in Figure 1. Sensors that we have figured out are listed in the left column. These will be addressed in further details below. In the right column, the research areas related to considered layer. As our objective is to optimize the operation of these three layers intelligently, the CR will also have a very strong bond with the emerging field of crosslayer optimization. This is what we find in the literature under the name \\u201copportunistic radio,\\u201d a restriction (following the model previously presented) of the physical layer of CR which is concerned with the spectrum management.<\\/li><\\/ul>"},"elements":[],"widgetType":"text-editor"}],"isInner":false}],"isInner":false},{"id":"knc1zia","elType":"section","settings":[],"elements":[{"id":"p7zr2g7","elType":"column","settings":{"_inline_size":"","_column_size":100},"elements":[{"id":"whm44tn","elType":"widget","settings":{"editor":"<h3><strong>Cognitive Radio Sensors<\\/strong><\\/h3>"},"elements":[],"widgetType":"text-editor"}],"isInner":false}],"isInner":false},{"id":"ib0w54p","elType":"section","settings":[],"elements":[{"id":"az0xmeb","elType":"column","settings":{"_inline_size":"","_column_size":100},"elements":[{"id":"1z1grom","elType":"widget","settings":{"image":{"url":"http:\\/\\/localhost\\/wordpress\\/wp-content\\/uploads\\/2017\\/05\\/SmartSensors2-1.png","id":588},"caption":"Tab 1. Classification list (not exhaustive) of sensors according to the environment","image_box_shadow_box_shadow_type":"yes"},"elements":[],"widgetType":"image"}],"isInner":false}],"isInner":false},{"id":"0xi5rf0","elType":"section","settings":[],"elements":[{"id":"4k696dv","elType":"column","settings":{"_inline_size":"","_column_size":100},"elements":[{"id":"qxhwt0y","elType":"widget","settings":{"image":{"url":"http:\\/\\/localhost\\/wordpress\\/wp-content\\/uploads\\/2017\\/05\\/SmartSensors3-1.png","id":587},"caption":"Tab 2. Classification of sensors based on simplified three layers model","image_box_shadow_box_shadow_type":"yes"},"elements":[],"widgetType":"image"}],"isInner":false}],"isInner":false},{"id":"5u17yld","elType":"section","settings":[],"elements":[{"id":"lm89g6r","elType":"column","settings":{"_inline_size":"","_column_size":100},"elements":[{"id":"1smrpbc","elType":"widget","settings":{"editor":"<h3><strong>The \\u00ab Sensorial Radio Bubble for Cognitive Radio\\u00bb<\\/strong><\\/h3><p>The concept of \\u201cSensorial Radio Bubble\\u201d (SRB) was defined by keeping in mind the conventional notion of \\u201cHuman Sensory Bubble\\u201d (for details see [PAL 07], [PAL 09]). This bubble is a multi-dimensional space around the equipment considered (Figure 3.), with one dimension per sensing capacity (exactly like \\u201chuman sensorial bubble\\u201d with its sensors: five senses, see Figure 2.) [REB 04]. We have extended this concept of human or animal bubble to the world of the inanimate objects such as CR equipment, thanks to their capabilities to take into account their environment. From this point of view, this work enters into a domain known as \\u201cbio-inspired systems.\\u201d Each dimension of the SRB can be represented by numerous parameters (such as temperature and time for a conventional thermometer). Therefore with each sensor Ci, there is an associated vector of parameters defined by: Vi = [Pi0, ..., Pij , ..., PiJ-1] with i = 0, ...,N -1 and j = 0, ..., J -1 where N is the total number of sensors considered and J is the number of parameters of the sensor Ci. One of these parameters can represent distance as in the case for certain sensors of \\u201chuman bubble\\u201d (hearing, sight, touch). In certain situations the vector may contain only a single parameter. Considering the simplified model of cognitive cycle given in Figure 1, the SRB i