(751, 1, '2017-05-10 09:23:35', '2017-05-10 07:23:35', '<a name="objectifs"></a>\r\n<pre>Software Radio Implementation on Reconfigurable Architectures</pre>\r\n<a name="objectifs"></a>\r\n<p align="justify">Software radio and <a href="http://www.rennes.supelec.fr/ren/rd/scee/themes/scee_cognitive-radio.en.html">cognitive radio</a> are based on processing architectures demanding a very high computing power and requiring multi-processing structures. Architectural constraints are therefore very demanding and the use of devices of different natures is often necessary. Reconfiguration management of software radio systems consequently involves complex techniques and methods. Devices may be as various as processors (micro-controlers or general purpose processors), DSPs, FPGAs, digital parameterizable ASICs, etc. We speak about HW heterogeneity.</p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<pre>Involved staff</pre>\r\n<p align="justify">Jacques PALICOT (Professor)\r\n<a href="http://www.rennes.supelec.fr/ren/perso/pleray/">Pierre LERAY</a> (Associate Professor)\r\n<a href="http://www.rennes.supelec.fr/ren/perso/ylouet/" target="_top">Yves LOUET</a> (Associate Professor)\r\n<a href="http://www.rennes.supelec.fr/ren/perso/cmoy/" target="_top">Christophe MOY</a> (Associate Professor)\r\n<a href="http://www.rennes.supelec.fr/ren/perso/vrodrigu/">Virgilio RODRIGUEZ</a> (post-doctor)\r\nAli AL GHOUWAYEL (doctor student)\r\nJean-Philippe DELAHAYE (doctor student)\r\nHongzhi WANG (doctor student))\r\nLoïg GODARD (doctor student))</p>\r\n<a name="archi_reconf"></a>\r\n<pre>FPGA dynamic partial reconfiguration architecture for software defined radio systems</pre>\r\n<p align="justify">Based on the study of several reconfiguration scenarios (at the standard, the mode or the bug-fixing level) a hierarchical distributed approach is priviledged. Combined with a multi-standard analysis (GSM, UMTS FDD, 802.11g) which provides rules of mapping of the SW processing functions on the heterogeneous HW devices, we propose a multi-layer reconfiguration management. 3 layers have been defined, each managing reconfiguration at different levels of granularity, but also in various locations inside the system, e.g. in HW components of different nature. High-level (standard level) management layer indeed is preferably dedicated to be implemented in a GPP for high-granularity reconfiguration, while low-level (algorithm level) managers may be mapped on DSPs or even embedded processor cores inside FPGAs in order to be as close as possible of the SW processing elements they manage. This reconfiguration hierarchical management is closely related with our parameterization and common operators studies also exposed in this page. In the specific context of reconfigurable hardware, this study particularly focuses on the partial and dynamic reconfiguration FPGAs, which we implement of Xilinx Virtex II components.</p>\r\n<p align="right"><small><i>Doctor student: Jean-Philippe DELAHAYE\r\nSupervisor: Jacques PALICOT</i>\r\n</small></p>\r\n<a name="archi_reconf2"></a>\r\n<pre>Distributed hierarchical management architecture for cognitive radio systems</pre>\r\n<p align="justify">This is an extension of the previous subject towards cognitive radios. A distributed hierarchical management is also proposed for the cognitive side of the system.</p>\r\n<p align="right"><small><i>Doctor student: Loïg GODARD\r\nSupervisor: <a href="http://www.rennes.supelec.fr/ren/perso/cmoy/" target="_top">Christophe MOY</a></i>\r\n</small></p>\r\n<a name="MIMO"></a>\r\n<pre>FPGA dynamic partial reconfiguration for software radio MIMO</pre>\r\n<p align="justify">This study focuses on the design of a specific flexible architecture for the implementation of MIMO signals detection on FPGA. The algorithm under investigation is the V-BLAST "Square Root" in a software radio context. The proposed architecture uses the CORDIC algorithm as an elementary operator. The optimization of HW resources is obtained by dynamically adapting the parallelism level to the computing power for a given MIMO configuration and a given data rate.</p>\r\n<p align="right"><small><i>Doctor student: Hongzhi WANG\r\nSupervisor : <a href="http://www.rennes.supelec.fr/ren/perso/pleray/">Pierre LERAY</a></i>\r\n</small></p>\r\n<a name="param"></a>\r\n<pre>FFT common operator and parameterization</pre>\r\n<p align="justify">Parameterization studies are a new specific field of software radio. Two types of parameterization can be distinguished: common funcions or common operators. The goal consists in finding a set of common operators (or a common function) at a the highest level of granularity which can keep genericity properties to be implemented for the maximum of processes of a multi-standard software radio terminal (including future standards). We are currently formalizing this approach in the frequency domain for processes usually done in the time domain until now, in order to take benefit of the FFT or butterfly common operator. A focus is done on the channel decoding functionalities.</p>\r\n<p align="right"><small><i>Doctor student: Ali AL GHOUWAYEL\r\nSupervisor : <a href="http://www.rennes.supelec.fr/ren/perso/ylouet/" target="_top">Yves LOUET</a></i>\r\n</small></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<pre>Cross-layer optimization for multi-standards software radio systems designed with parameterization techniques</pre>\r\n<p align="justify">The lab is involved in an original parameterization approach based on a "common opertor" perspective for the cross-layer optimization for multi-standards software radio systems. The main objective consists in factorizing processing entities between as many as possible of the algorithms of a plurality of standards in order to minmize the reconfiguration overheads needed to switch from one standard (GSM for example) to another (UMTS for example). This permits to avoid time and bandpass consuming downloading procedures for the reconfiguration of the system during a standard switch, since the same set of operators should be able of running both standards while only changing parameters of the operators.\r\nA model has been defined, based on an hypergraph description of the multi-standard system. First optimization algorithms are defined. Costs involved in the optimization are still to be refined. Expected results are the choice of the set of common operators to be implemented for different combinations of software radio multi-standards systems.</p>\r\n<p align="right"><small><i>Post-doctor: <a href="http://www.rennes.supelec.fr/ren/perso/vrodrigu/">Virgilio RODRIGUEZ</a>\r\nSupervisor: <a href="http://www.rennes.supelec.fr/ren/perso/cmoy/" target="_top">Christophe MOY</a></i></small></p>', 'Reconfigurable Architectures', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '126-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-05-10 09:23:35', '2017-05-10 07:23:35', '', 126, 'http://localhost/wordpress/index.php/2017/05/10/126-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(752, 1, '2017-05-10 09:24:21', '2017-05-10 07:24:21', '<center>FACE ANALYSIS AND SYNTHESIS</center>&nbsp;\r\n<h2><b>PEOPLE</b></h2>\r\n<a href="http://www.rennes.supelec.fr/ren/perso/chabert_car/">Caroline Chabert</a> ( Ph.D. Student 20012-2015 )\r\nFace retargetting\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.rennes.supelec.fr/ren/perso/manceau_jer/">Jérôme Manceau</a> ( Ph.D. Student 20012-2015 )\r\nFace cloning\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.rennes.supelec.fr/ren/perso/salam_han/">Hanan Salam</a> ( Ph.D. Student 20010-2013 )\r\n3D objects face model\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.rennes.supelec.fr/ren/perso/rseguier/">Renaud Séguier</a> (PhD, HDR )\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.rennes.supelec.fr/ren/perso/soladie_cat/">Catherine Soladie</a> ( Ph.D. Student 20010-2013 )\r\nOnline expression analysis\r\n<h2><b>RESEARCH TOPICS</b></h2>\r\n<a name="Themes"></a>We detect, analyse and synthesize faces for Video-Telephony, Man-Machine Interaction and Software Radio. Forces are concentrated on 2D and 2.5D Active Appearence Models (AAM) for wich we develop different pre-processing and new optimisation algorithms. Those AAM are implemented in real-time for embedded systems.\r\n<h2><b>RESEARCH PROJECTS</b></h2>\r\n<h3><b>REPLICA, 2012 - 2015</b></h3>\r\nRehabilitation of facial praxis among cerebral paralysis via interactive Avatar.\r\nNational collaborative project "ANR - TECHSAN"\r\nLeader: University of Rennes II (M2S, CRP2C).\r\nPartners: Saint Maurice Hospital, Dynamixyz, Supélec.\r\nContributions:\r\nSpecification, metrics analysis: University of Rennes II\r\nTests and validations: Saint Maurice Hospital\r\nFacial animation: Dynamixyz\r\nFace analysis: Supélec\r\n<h3><b>SKETCHER, 2012 - 2013</b></h3>\r\nDevelopment of a Rapid E-Learning tool.\r\nRegional "PME" project funded by Région Bretagne.\r\nLeader: Dynamixyz.\r\nPartners: Voxygen, Supélec.\r\nContributions:\r\nSpecification, Integration: Dynamixyz\r\nExpressiv voice synthesis: Voxygen\r\nFace and gesture analysis: Supélec\r\n<h3><b>IMMERSIVITE, 2011 - 2012</b></h3>\r\nIMmersion dans un environnement de forMation convERsationnel, expresSIf et VIrTuEl\r\nWeb site : <a href="http://www.immersivite.fr/">www.immersivite.fr </a>\r\nIntegration of man-machine interfaces for serious-game. The objective is to increase the interaction efficienty between students and virtual characters.\r\nRegional "PME" project funded by Région Bretagne.\r\nLeader: Dialonics.\r\nPartners: CERV, Dynamixyz, Supélec, Virtualis.\r\nContributions:\r\n3D virtual world: CERV\r\nFacial animation: Dynamixyz\r\nFace and gesture analysis: Supélec\r\nNatural language inetraction: Dialonics\r\nProduct integration: Virtualis\r\n<h3><b>IMMEMO, 2010 - 2013</b></h3>\r\nIMMersion 3D basée sur l''interaction EMOtionnelle\r\nWeb site : <a href="http://www.rennes.supelec.fr/immemo/">www.rennes.supelec.fr/immemo/ </a>\r\nThis industrial research project aims at designing a plug-in making it possible to capture and recognize the expressions of the face of a person immersed in a 3D virtual world for serious-game. The plugin will facilitate her interaction with an autonomous conversational agent (ACA) of which the behavior will adapt in a semi-automatic way to that of learning immersive person.\r\nNational collaborative project "ANR - CONTINT"\r\nLeader: Supélec\r\nPartners: Artefacto, Institut Telecom, ISIR.\r\nContributions:\r\n3D virtual world: Artefacto\r\nFacial expressions analysis: ISIR, Supélec\r\nMulti-modal interaction: Institut Telecom\r\n<h2><b>PUBLICATIONS</b></h2>\r\n<a href="http://www.rennes.supelec.fr/ren/perso/rseguier/publications.php">Patents, Journals, Conferences</a>\r\n<h2><b>DEMO</b></h2>\r\n<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-150" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/HigherLayer.jpg" alt="" width="320" height="240" />\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n[embed]http://www.dailymotion.com/video/x2e30d_avatar_tech[/embed]\r\n\r\nAvatar\r\n<h2><b>PAST RESEARCH PROJECTS</b></h2>\r\n<h3><b>Lipsync</b></h3>\r\nRegional project "fonds de maturation" funded by Région Bretagne and Feder.\r\nSynchronization of 3D character lips movment and shapes on an audio input.\r\nEnded in 2010.\r\n<h2><b>PAST RESEARCHERS</b></h2>\r\n<a href="http://www.rennes.supelec.fr/ren/perso/nstoiber/">Nicolas Stoiber</a> ( Ph.D. Student 2007-2010 )\r\nFacial Expressiveness of Virtual Characters\r\n\r\nBiyi Lin ( Ph.D. Student 2008-2009 )\r\nEmotion Classification\r\n\r\nAbdul Sattar ( Ph.D. Student 2006-2009, Post Doc 2010 )\r\n3D face Active Appearence Models\r\nLip Synchronization\r\n\r\nYasser Aidarous ( Ph.D. Student 2005-2008 )\r\nActive Appearence Models optimisation for face analysis\r\n\r\n<a href="http://sylvain.legallou.fr/">Sylvain Le Gallou</a> ( Ph.D. Student 2004-2007 )\r\nActive Appearence Models for face gesture analysis\r\n\r\nOlivier Dumas ( Ph.D. Student 2003-2006 )\r\n3D face modelisation\r\n\r\nNicolas Cladel ( Ph.D. student 2002-2005 )\r\nMulti-objectives snakes optimisation : application on mouth segmentation\r\n\r\nDavid Mercier ( Ph.D. student 2000-2003)\r\nLipsreading\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Higher Layer', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '149-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-05-10 09:24:21', '2017-05-10 07:24:21', '', 149, 'http://localhost/wordpress/index.php/2017/05/10/149-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
