(775, 1, '2017-05-10 14:04:46', '2017-05-10 12:04:46', '<p>1. 1. The three layers model of the Cognitive Radio</p>		\n					<figure>\n		<img width="1024" height="544" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/SmartSensors1-1-1024x544.png" alt="" srcset="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/SmartSensors1-1-1024x544.png 1024w, http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/SmartSensors1-1-300x159.png 300w, http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/SmartSensors1-1-768x408.png 768w, http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/SmartSensors1-1.png 1092w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" />				<figcaption>Fig. 1</figcaption>\n					</figure>\n		<h2> </h2><p>To explain this model, we cut the model of Figure 1. into three main layers:</p><ul><li>A <a href="http://www.rennes.supelec.fr/ren/rd/scee/themes/scee_ti.html">high level layer</a>, which contains primarily the application layer and man-machine type interfaces, called higher layer;</li><li><a href="http://www.rennes.supelec.fr/ren/rd/scee/themes/scee_capteurs-intermediaires.html">An intermediate layer</a> containing transport and network layers;</li><li>A <a href="http://www.rennes.supelec.fr/ren/rd/scee/themes/scee_freq.html">low level layer</a>, which contains MAC and physical layers, called the lower layer.The set of these layers runs on a SR platform (possibly ideal), but this model also runs on a software defined radio platform . These software radio platforms are based on hardware architecture of execution, which in general is heterogeneous. This platform is ideally hidden via an abstraction layer that offers a transparency in terms of implementation of software components to process the signals.</li><li>We further illustrate the model in Figure 1. Sensors that we have figured out are listed in the left column. These will be addressed in further details below. In the right column, the research areas related to considered layer. As our objective is to optimize the operation of these three layers intelligently, the CR will also have a very strong bond with the emerging field of crosslayer optimization. This is what we find in the literature under the name “opportunistic radio,” a restriction (following the model previously presented) of the physical layer of CR which is concerned with the spectrum management.</li></ul><p>2. 2. Cognitive Radio Sensors</p><p>Je suis un bloc de texte. Cliquez sur le bouton modifier pour changer ce texte. Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit. Ut elit tellus, luctus nec ullamcorper mattis, pulvinar dapibus leo.</p>		\n					<figure>\n		<img width="383" height="599" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/SmartSensors2-1.png" alt="" srcset="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/SmartSensors2-1.png 383w, http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/SmartSensors2-1-192x300.png 192w" sizes="(max-width: 383px) 100vw, 383px" />				<figcaption>Tab 1. Classification list (not exhaustive) of sensors according to the environment</figcaption>\n					</figure>\n					<figure>\n		<img width="609" height="592" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/SmartSensors3-1.png" alt="" srcset="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/SmartSensors3-1.png 609w, http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/SmartSensors3-1-300x292.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 609px) 100vw, 609px" />				<figcaption>Tab 2. Classification of sensors based on simplified three layers model</figcaption>\n					</figure>\n		<h2>3. The « Sensorial Radio Bubble for Cognitive Radio»</h2><p>The concept of “Sensorial Radio Bubble” (SRB) was defined by keeping in mind the conventional notion of “Human Sensory Bubble” (for details see [PAL 07], [PAL 09]). This bubble is a multi-dimensional space around the equipment considered (Figure 3.), with one dimension per sensing capacity (exactly like “human sensorial bubble” with its sensors: five senses, see Figure 2.) [REB 04]. We have extended this concept of human or animal bubble to the world of the inanimate objects such as CR equipment, thanks to their capabilities to take into account their environment. From this point of view, this work enters into a domain known as “bio-inspired systems.” Each dimension of the SRB can be represented by numerous parameters (such as temperature and time for a conventional thermometer). Therefore with each sensor Ci, there is an associated vector of parameters defined by: Vi = [Pi0, ..., Pij , ..., PiJ-1] with i = 0, ...,N -1 and j = 0, ..., J -1 where N is the total number of sensors considered and J is the number of parameters of the sensor Ci. One of these parameters can represent distance as in the case for certain sensors of “human bubble” (hearing, sight, touch). In certain situations the vector may contain only a single parameter. Considering the simplified model of cognitive cycle given in Figure 1, the SRB is clearly located in the function “environment analysis.”</p>		\n					<figure>\n		<img width="320" height="296" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/SmartSensors4-1.png" alt="" srcset="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/SmartSensors4-1.png 320w, http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/SmartSensors4-1-300x278.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 320px) 100vw, 320px" />				<figcaption>Figure 2. La Bulle Humaine </figcaption>\n					</figure>\n					<figure>\n		<img width="343" height="295" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/SmartSensors5-1.png" alt="" srcset="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/SmartSensors5-1.png 343w, http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/SmartSensors5-1-300x258.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 343px) 100vw, 343px" />				<figcaption>Figure 3. La bulle sensorielle RI</figcaption>\n					</figure>\n		<p align="justify">[PAL 07] PALICOT J., HACHEMANI R., MOY C., « La bulle sensorielle radio intelligente », Revue de l’électricité et de l’électronique, n° 9, 2007. [PAL 09] PALICOT J., MOY C., HACHEMANI R., «Multilayer sensors for the sensorial radio bubble », Physical Communication, vol. 2, p. 151-165, mai 2009.</p><p>[REB 04] REBHAN P., « Bubbles of Perception : exploring the limits and the future of human perception », http ://www.rebfile.com/bop-images/Bubbles of Perception Ebook.pdf., 2004.</p><p>[Pal] Palicot J (sous la direction de), De la radio logicielle à la radio intelligente, Collection Télécom, Lavoisier Librairie, june 2010 ; ISBN : 978-2-7462-2598-5</p>', 'Smart Sensors', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '131-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-05-10 14:04:46', '2017-05-10 12:04:46', '', 131, 'http://localhost/wordpress/index.php/2017/05/10/131-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(776, 1, '2017-05-10 14:05:32', '2017-05-10 12:05:32', '<p>1. 1. The three layers model of the Cognitive Radio</p>		\n					<figure>\n		<img width="1024" height="544" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/SmartSensors1-1-1024x544.png" alt="" srcset="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/SmartSensors1-1-1024x544.png 1024w, http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/SmartSensors1-1-300x159.png 300w, http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/SmartSensors1-1-768x408.png 768w, http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/SmartSensors1-1.png 1092w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" />				<figcaption>Fig. 1</figcaption>\n					</figure>\n		<h2> </h2><p>To explain this model, we cut the model of Figure 1. into three main layers:</p><ul><li>A <a href="http://www.rennes.supelec.fr/ren/rd/scee/themes/scee_ti.html">high level layer</a>, which contains primarily the application layer and man-machine type interfaces, called higher layer;</li><li><a href="http://www.rennes.supelec.fr/ren/rd/scee/themes/scee_capteurs-intermediaires.html">An intermediate layer</a> containing transport and network layers;</li><li>A <a href="http://www.rennes.supelec.fr/ren/rd/scee/themes/scee_freq.html">low level layer</a>, which contains MAC and physical layers, called the lower layer.The set of these layers runs on a SR platform (possibly ideal), but this model also runs on a software defined radio platform . These software radio platforms are based on hardware architecture of execution, which in general is heterogeneous. This platform is ideally hidden via an abstraction layer that offers a transparency in terms of implementation of software components to process the signals.</li><li>We further illustrate the model in Figure 1. Sensors that we have figured out are listed in the left column. These will be addressed in further details below. In the right column, the research areas related to considered layer. As our objective is to optimize the operation of these three layers intelligently, the CR will also have a very strong bond with the emerging field of crosslayer optimization. This is what we find in the literature under the name “opportunistic radio,” a restriction (following the model previously presented) of the physical layer of CR which is concerned with the spectrum management.</li></ul><p>2. 2. Cognitive Radio Sensors</p>		\n					<figure>\n		<img width="383" height="599" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/SmartSensors2-1.png" alt="" srcset="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/SmartSensors2-1.png 383w, http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/SmartSensors2-1-192x300.png 192w" sizes="(max-width: 383px) 100vw, 383px" />				<figcaption>Tab 1. Classification list (not exhaustive) of sensors according to the environment</figcaption>\n					</figure>\n					<figure>\n		<img width="609" height="592" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/SmartSensors3-1.png" alt="" srcset="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/SmartSensors3-1.png 609w, http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/SmartSensors3-1-300x292.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 609px) 100vw, 609px" />				<figcaption>Tab 2. Classification of sensors based on simplified three layers model</figcaption>\n					</figure>\n		<p>3. The « Sensorial Radio Bubble for Cognitive Radio»</p><p>The concept of “Sensorial Radio Bubble” (SRB) was defined by keeping in mind the conventional notion of “Human Sensory Bubble” (for details see [PAL 07], [PAL 09]). This bubble is a multi-dimensional space around the equipment considered (Figure 3.), with one dimension per sensing capacity (exactly like “human sensorial bubble” with its sensors: five senses, see Figure 2.) [REB 04]. We have extended this concept of human or animal bubble to the world of the inanimate objects such as CR equipment, thanks to their capabilities to take into account their environment. From this point of view, this work enters into a domain known as “bio-inspired systems.” Each dimension of the SRB can be represented by numerous parameters (such as temperature and time for a conventional thermometer). Therefore with each sensor Ci, there is an associated vector of parameters defined by: Vi = [Pi0, ..., Pij , ..., PiJ-1] with i = 0, ...,N -1 and j = 0, ..., J -1 where N is the total number of sensors considered and J is the number of parameters of the sensor Ci. One of these parameters can represent distance as in the case for certain sensors of “human bubble” (hearing, sight, touch). In certain situations the vector may contain only a single parameter. Considering the simplified model of cognitive cycle given in Figure 1, the SRB is clearly located in the function “environment analysis.”</p>		\n					<figure>\n		<img width="320" height="296" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/SmartSensors4-1.png" alt="" srcset="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/SmartSensors4-1.png 320w, http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/SmartSensors4-1-300x278.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 320px) 100vw, 320px" />				<figcaption>Figure 2. La Bulle Humaine </figcaption>\n					</figure>\n					<figure>\n		<img width="343" height="295" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/SmartSensors5-1.png" alt="" srcset="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/SmartSensors5-1.png 343w, http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/SmartSensors5-1-300x258.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 343px) 100vw, 343px" />				<figcaption>Figure 3. La bulle sensorielle RI</figcaption>\n					</figure>\n		<p align="justify">[PAL 07] PALICOT J., HACHEMANI R., MOY C., « La bulle sensorielle radio intelligente », Revue de l’électricité et de l’électronique, n° 9, 2007. [PAL 09] PALICOT J., MOY C., HACHEMANI R., «Multilayer sensors for the sensorial radio bubble », Physical Communication, vol. 2, p. 151-165, mai 2009.</p><p>[REB 04] REBHAN P., « Bubbles of Perception : exploring the limits and the future of human perception », http ://www.rebfile.com/bop-images/Bubbles of Perception Ebook.pdf., 2004.</p><p>[Pal] Palicot J (sous la direction de), De la radio logicielle à la radio intelligente, Collection Télécom, Lavoisier Librairie, june 2010 ; ISBN : 978-2-7462-2598-5</p>', 'Smart Sensors', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '131-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-05-10 14:05:32', '2017-05-10 12:05:32', '', 131, 'http://localhost/wordpress/index.php/2017/05/10/131-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
