(790, 1, '2017-05-10 14:42:20', '2017-05-10 12:42:20', '<p> </p><h3><strong>Software Radio Implementation on Reconfigurable Architectures</strong></h3><p align="justify">Software radio and <a href="http://www.rennes.supelec.fr/ren/rd/scee/themes/scee_cognitive-radio.en.html">cognitive radio</a> are based on processing architectures demanding a very high computing power and requiring multi-processing structures. Architectural constraints are therefore very demanding and the use of devices of different natures is often necessary. Reconfiguration management of software radio systems consequently involves complex techniques and methods. Devices may be as various as processors (micro-controlers or general purpose processors), DSPs, FPGAs, digital parameterizable ASICs, etc. We speak about HW heterogeneity.</p><p> </p><h3><strong>Involved staff</strong></h3><p align="justify">Jacques PALICOT (Professor)<br /> <a href="http://www.rennes.supelec.fr/ren/perso/pleray/">Pierre LERAY</a> (Associate Professor)<br /> <a href="http://www.rennes.supelec.fr/ren/perso/ylouet/" target="_top">Yves LOUET</a> (Associate Professor)<br /> <a href="http://www.rennes.supelec.fr/ren/perso/cmoy/" target="_top">Christophe MOY</a> (Associate Professor)<br /> <a href="http://www.rennes.supelec.fr/ren/perso/vrodrigu/">Virgilio RODRIGUEZ</a> (post-doctor)<br /> Ali AL GHOUWAYEL (doctor student)<br /> Jean-Philippe DELAHAYE (doctor student)<br /> Hongzhi WANG (doctor student))<br /> Loïg GODARD (doctor student))</p><p><a name="archi_reconf"></a></p><h3><strong>FPGA dynamic partial reconfiguration architecture for software defined radio systems</strong></h3><p align="justify">Based on the study of several reconfiguration scenarios (at the standard, the mode or the bug-fixing level) a hierarchical distributed approach is priviledged. Combined with a multi-standard analysis (GSM, UMTS FDD, 802.11g) which provides rules of mapping of the SW processing functions on the heterogeneous HW devices, we propose a multi-layer reconfiguration management. 3 layers have been defined, each managing reconfiguration at different levels of granularity, but also in various locations inside the system, e.g. in HW components of different nature. High-level (standard level) management layer indeed is preferably dedicated to be implemented in a GPP for high-granularity reconfiguration, while low-level (algorithm level) managers may be mapped on DSPs or even embedded processor cores inside FPGAs in order to be as close as possible of the SW processing elements they manage. This reconfiguration hierarchical management is closely related with our parameterization and common operators studies also exposed in this page. In the specific context of reconfigurable hardware, this study particularly focuses on the partial and dynamic reconfiguration FPGAs, which we implement of Xilinx Virtex II components.</p><p align="right"><small><i>Doctor student: Jean-Philippe DELAHAYE<br /> Supervisor: Jacques PALICOT</i><br /> </small></p><p><a name="archi_reconf2"></a></p><h3><strong>Distributed hierarchical management architecture for cognitive radio systems</strong></h3><p align="justify">This is an extension of the previous subject towards cognitive radios. A distributed hierarchical management is also proposed for the cognitive side of the system.</p><p align="right"><small><i>Doctor student: Loïg GODARD<br /> Supervisor: <a href="http://www.rennes.supelec.fr/ren/perso/cmoy/" target="_top">Christophe MOY</a></i><br /> </small></p><p><a name="MIMO"></a></p><h3><strong>FPGA dynamic partial reconfiguration for software radio MIMO</strong></h3><h3 align="justify">This study focuses on the design of a specific flexible architecture for the implementation of MIMO signals detection on FPGA. The algorithm under investigation is the V-BLAST "Square Root" in a software radio context. The proposed architecture uses the CORDIC algorithm as an elementary operator. The optimization of HW resources is obtained by dynamically adapting the parallelism level to the computing power for a given MIMO configuration and a given data rate.</h3><p align="right"><small><i>Doctor student: Hongzhi WANG<br /> Supervisor : <a href="http://www.rennes.supelec.fr/ren/perso/pleray/">Pierre LERAY</a></i><br /> </small></p><p><a name="param"></a></p><h3><strong>FFT common operator and parameterization</strong></h3><p align="justify">Parameterization studies are a new specific field of software radio. Two types of parameterization can be distinguished: common funcions or common operators. The goal consists in finding a set of common operators (or a common function) at a the highest level of granularity which can keep genericity properties to be implemented for the maximum of processes of a multi-standard software radio terminal (including future standards). We are currently formalizing this approach in the frequency domain for processes usually done in the time domain until now, in order to take benefit of the FFT or butterfly common operator. A focus is done on the channel decoding functionalities.</p><p align="right"><small><i>Doctor student: Ali AL GHOUWAYEL<br /> Supervisor : <a href="http://www.rennes.supelec.fr/ren/perso/ylouet/" target="_top">Yves LOUET</a></i><br /> </small></p><p> </p><h3><strong>Cross-layer optimization for multi-standards software radio systems designed with parameterization techniques</strong></h3><p align="justify">The lab is involved in an original parameterization approach based on a "common opertor" perspective for the cross-layer optimization for multi-standards software radio systems. The main objective consists in factorizing processing entities between as many as possible of the algorithms of a plurality of standards in order to minmize the reconfiguration overheads needed to switch from one standard (GSM for example) to another (UMTS for example). This permits to avoid time and bandpass consuming downloading procedures for the reconfiguration of the system during a standard switch, since the same set of operators should be able of running both standards while only changing parameters of the operators.<br />A model has been defined, based on an hypergraph description of the multi-standard system. First optimization algorithms are defined. Costs involved in the optimization are still to be refined. Expected results are the choice of the set of common operators to be implemented for different combinations of software radio multi-standards systems.</p><p align="right"><small><i>Post-doctor: <a href="http://www.rennes.supelec.fr/ren/perso/vrodrigu/">Virgilio RODRIGUEZ</a><br />Supervisor: <a href="http://www.rennes.supelec.fr/ren/perso/cmoy/" target="_top">Christophe MOY</a></i></small></p>', 'Reconfigurable Architectures', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '126-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-05-10 14:42:20', '2017-05-10 12:42:20', '', 126, 'http://localhost/wordpress/index.php/2017/05/10/126-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(791, 1, '2017-05-10 14:44:45', '2017-05-10 12:44:45', '<h3><strong>The three layers model of the Cognitive Radio</strong></h3>		\n					<figure>\n		<img width="1024" height="544" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/SmartSensors1-1-1024x544.png" alt="" srcset="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/SmartSensors1-1-1024x544.png 1024w, http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/SmartSensors1-1-300x159.png 300w, http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/SmartSensors1-1-768x408.png 768w, http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/SmartSensors1-1.png 1092w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" />				<figcaption>Fig. 1</figcaption>\n					</figure>\n		<h3><strong>To explain this model, we cut the model of Figure 1. into three main layers</strong></h3><ul><li>A <a href="http://www.rennes.supelec.fr/ren/rd/scee/themes/scee_ti.html">high level layer</a>, which contains primarily the application layer and man-machine type interfaces, called higher layer;</li><li><a href="http://www.rennes.supelec.fr/ren/rd/scee/themes/scee_capteurs-intermediaires.html">An intermediate layer</a> containing transport and network layers;</li><li>A <a href="http://www.rennes.supelec.fr/ren/rd/scee/themes/scee_freq.html">low level layer</a>, which contains MAC and physical layers, called the lower layer.The set of these layers runs on a SR platform (possibly ideal), but this model also runs on a software defined radio platform . These software radio platforms are based on hardware architecture of execution, which in general is heterogeneous. This platform is ideally hidden via an abstraction layer that offers a transparency in terms of implementation of software components to process the signals.</li><li>We further illustrate the model in Figure 1. Sensors that we have figured out are listed in the left column. These will be addressed in further details below. In the right column, the research areas related to considered layer. As our objective is to optimize the operation of these three layers intelligently, the CR will also have a very strong bond with the emerging field of crosslayer optimization. This is what we find in the literature under the name “opportunistic radio,” a restriction (following the model previously presented) of the physical layer of CR which is concerned with the spectrum management.</li></ul><h3><strong>Cognitive Radio Sensors</strong></h3>		\n					<figure>\n		<img width="383" height="599" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/SmartSensors2-1.png" alt="" srcset="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/SmartSensors2-1.png 383w, http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/SmartSensors2-1-192x300.png 192w" sizes="(max-width: 383px) 100vw, 383px" />				<figcaption>Tab 1. Classification list (not exhaustive) of sensors according to the environment</figcaption>\n					</figure>\n					<figure>\n		<img width="609" height="592" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/SmartSensors3-1.png" alt="" srcset="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/SmartSensors3-1.png 609w, http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/SmartSensors3-1-300x292.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 609px) 100vw, 609px" />				<figcaption>Tab 2. Classification of sensors based on simplified three layers model</figcaption>\n					</figure>\n		<h3><strong>The « Sensorial Radio Bubble for Cognitive Radio»</strong></h3><p>The concept of “Sensorial Radio Bubble” (SRB) was defined by keeping in mind the conventional notion of “Human Sensory Bubble” (for details see [PAL 07], [PAL 09]). This bubble is a multi-dimensional space around the equipment considered (Figure 3.), with one dimension per sensing capacity (exactly like “human sensorial bubble” with its sensors: five senses, see Figure 2.) [REB 04]. We have extended this concept of human or animal bubble to the world of the inanimate objects such as CR equipment, thanks to their capabilities to take into account their environment. From this point of view, this work enters into a domain known as “bio-inspired systems.” Each dimension of the SRB can be represented by numerous parameters (such as temperature and time for a conventional thermometer). Therefore with each sensor Ci, there is an associated vector of parameters defined by: Vi = [Pi0, ..., Pij , ..., PiJ-1] with i = 0, ...,N -1 and j = 0, ..., J -1 where N is the total number of sensors considered and J is the number of parameters of the sensor Ci. One of these parameters can represent distance as in the case for certain sensors of “human bubble” (hearing, sight, touch). In certain situations the vector may contain only a single parameter. Considering the simplified model of cognitive cycle given in Figure 1, the SRB is clearly located in the function “environment analysis.”</p>		\n					<figure>\n		<img width="320" height="296" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/SmartSensors4-1.png" alt="" srcset="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/SmartSensors4-1.png 320w, http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/SmartSensors4-1-300x278.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 320px) 100vw, 320px" />				<figcaption>Figure 2. La Bulle Humaine </figcaption>\n					</figure>\n					<figure>\n		<img width="343" height="295" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/SmartSensors5-1.png" alt="" srcset="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/SmartSensors5-1.png 343w, http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/SmartSensors5-1-300x258.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 343px) 100vw, 343px" />				<figcaption>Figure 3. La bulle sensorielle RI</figcaption>\n					</figure>\n		<p align="justify">[PAL 07] PALICOT J., HACHEMANI R., MOY C., « La bulle sensorielle radio intelligente », Revue de l’électricité et de l’électronique, n° 9, 2007. [PAL 09] PALICOT J., MOY C., HACHEMANI R., «Multilayer sensors for the sensorial radio bubble », Physical Communication, vol. 2, p. 151-165, mai 2009.</p><p>[REB 04] REBHAN P., « Bubbles of Perception : exploring the limits and the future of human perception », http ://www.rebfile.com/bop-images/Bubbles of Perception Ebook.pdf., 2004.</p><p>[Pal] Palicot J (sous la direction de), De la radio logicielle à la radio intelligente, Collection Télécom, Lavoisier Librairie, june 2010 ; ISBN : 978-2-7462-2598-5</p>', 'Smart Sensors', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '131-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-05-10 14:44:45', '2017-05-10 12:44:45', '', 131, 'http://localhost/wordpress/index.php/2017/05/10/131-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(792, 1, '2017-05-10 14:50:57', '2017-05-10 12:50:57', '<h2 style="text-align: left;"><strong>FACE ANALYSIS AND SYNTHESIS</strong></h2><p> </p><h3><strong>PEOPLE</strong></h3><p><a href="http://www.rennes.supelec.fr/ren/perso/chabert_car/">Caroline Chabert</a> ( Ph.D. Student 20012-2015 )<br /> Face retargetting</p><p><a href="http://www.rennes.supelec.fr/ren/perso/manceau_jer/">Jérôme Manceau</a> ( Ph.D. Student 20012-2015 )<br /> Face cloning</p><p><a href="http://www.rennes.supelec.fr/ren/perso/salam_han/">Hanan Salam</a> ( Ph.D. Student 20010-2013 )<br /> 3D objects face model</p><p><a href="http://www.rennes.supelec.fr/ren/perso/rseguier/">Renaud Séguier</a> (PhD, HDR )</p><p><a href="http://www.rennes.supelec.fr/ren/perso/soladie_cat/">Catherine Soladie</a> ( Ph.D. Student 20010-2013 )<br /> Online expression analysis</p><h3>RESEARCH TOPICS</h3><p>We detect, analyse and synthesize faces for Video-Telephony, Man-Machine Interaction and Software Radio. Forces are concentrated on 2D and 2.5D Active Appearence Models (AAM) for wich we develop different pre-processing and new optimisation algorithms. Those AAM are implemented in real-time for embedded systems.</p><h2><strong>RESEARCH PROJECTS</strong></h2><h3><strong>REPLICA, 2012 - 2015</strong></h3><p>Rehabilitation of facial praxis among cerebral paralysis via interactive Avatar.<br /> National collaborative project "ANR - TECHSAN"<br /> Leader: University of Rennes II (M2S, CRP2C).<br /> Partners: Saint Maurice Hospital, Dynamixyz, Supélec.<br /> Contributions:<br /> Specification, metrics analysis: University of Rennes II<br /> Tests and validations: Saint Maurice Hospital<br /> Facial animation: Dynamixyz<br /> Face analysis: Supélec</p><h3><b>SKETCHER, 2012 - 2013</b></h3><p>Development of a Rapid E-Learning tool.<br /> Regional "PME" project funded by Région Bretagne.<br /> Leader: Dynamixyz.<br /> Partners: Voxygen, Supélec.<br /> Contributions:<br /> Specification, Integration: Dynamixyz<br /> Expressiv voice synthesis: Voxygen<br /> Face and gesture analysis: Supélec</p><p><b>IMMERSIVITE, 2011 - 2012</b></p><p>IMmersion dans un environnement de forMation convERsationnel, expresSIf et VIrTuEl<br /> Web site : <a href="http://www.immersivite.fr/">www.immersivite.fr </a><br /> Integration of man-machine interfaces for serious-game. The objective is to increase the interaction efficienty between students and virtual characters.<br /> Regional "PME" project funded by Région Bretagne.<br /> Leader: Dialonics.<br /> Partners: CERV, Dynamixyz, Supélec, Virtualis.<br /> Contributions:<br /> 3D virtual world: CERV<br /> Facial animation: Dynamixyz<br /> Face and gesture analysis: Supélec<br /> Natural language inetraction: Dialonics<br /> Product integration: Virtualis</p><h3><b>IMMEMO, 2010 - 2013</b></h3><p>IMMersion 3D basée sur l''interaction EMOtionnelle<br /> Web site : <a href="http://www.rennes.supelec.fr/immemo/">www.rennes.supelec.fr/immemo/ </a><br /> This industrial research project aims at designing a plug-in making it possible to capture and recognize the expressions of the face of a person immersed in a 3D virtual world for serious-game. The plugin will facilitate her interaction with an autonomous conversational agent (ACA) of which the behavior will adapt in a semi-automatic way to that of learning immersive person.<br /> National collaborative project "ANR - CONTINT"<br /> Leader: Supélec<br /> Partners: Artefacto, Institut Telecom, ISIR.<br /> Contributions:<br /> 3D virtual world: Artefacto<br /> Facial expressions analysis: ISIR, Supélec<br /> Multi-modal interaction: Institut Telecom</p><h2><strong>PUBLICATIONS</strong></h2><p><a href="http://www.rennes.supelec.fr/ren/perso/rseguier/publications.php">Patents, Journals, Conferences</a></p><p><b>DEMO</b></p><p><img src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/HigherLayer.jpg" alt="" width="320" height="240" /></p><p>[embed]http://www.dailymotion.com/video/x2e30d_avatar_tech[/embed]</p><p>Avatar</p><h2><b>PAST RESEARCH PROJECTS</b></h2><h3><b>Lipsync</b></h3><p>Regional project "fonds de maturation" funded by Région Bretagne and Feder.<br /> Synchronization of 3D character lips movment and shapes on an audio input.<br /> Ended in 2010.</p><h2><b>PAST RESEARCHERS</b></h2><p><a href="http://www.rennes.supelec.fr/ren/perso/nstoiber/">Nicolas Stoiber</a> ( Ph.D. Student 2007-2010 )<br /> Facial Expressiveness of Virtual Characters</p><p>Biyi Lin ( Ph.D. Student 2008-2009 )<br /> Emotion Classification</p><p>Abdul Sattar ( Ph.D. Student 2006-2009, Post Doc 2010 )<br /> 3D face Active Appearence Models<br /> Lip Synchronization</p><p>Yasser Aidarous ( Ph.D. Student 2005-2008 )<br /> Active Appearence Models optimisation for face analysis</p><p><a href="http://sylvain.legallou.fr/">Sylvain Le Gallou</a> ( Ph.D. Student 2004-2007 )<br /> Active Appearence Models for face gesture analysis</p><p>Olivier Dumas ( Ph.D. Student 2003-2006 )<br /> 3D face modelisation</p><p>Nicolas Cladel ( Ph.D. student 2002-2005 )<br /> Multi-objectives snakes optimisation : application on mouth segmentation</p><p>David Mercier ( Ph.D. student 2000-2003)<br /> Lipsreading</p>', 'Higher Layer', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '149-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-05-10 14:50:57', '2017-05-10 12:50:57', '', 149, 'http://localhost/wordpress/index.php/2017/05/10/149-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(793, 1, '2017-05-10 14:53:03', '2017-05-10 12:53:03', '<h2><strong>Optimisation de ressources fréquentielles</strong></h2><p>Following our previous model (see table 2), sensors of the lower layer comprise, among others, the physical layer sensors and particularly the hole detection sensor.<br /> One of the main objectives of Cognitive Radio is to reach an efficient spectrum management by using free bands in the spectrum. This implies to observe if the received signal, at any time, comprises only noise or also a telecommunication signal.</p><h2><strong>Hole detection sensor</strong></h2><p>This sensor is extensively studied in the literature under the name, sensing. The CR is often limited to this sensor for detecting holes (or white spaces) in the spectrum as already discussed in Chapter 1. Cognitive radios require that the secondary network users are able to detect free spaces in the spectrum and use them in such a way that they do not interfere with the transmissions of the primary network. The quality of service required by the primary network will be otherwise significantly decreased. The problem of detection of primary network activity can be cast as a simple energy detection problem, for which various work efforts and methods exist since 1960. See Chapter 3 of book [Pal].</p><p>In this area two thesis have been defended in 2008 and in 2013:</p><ul><li><a href="http://www.rennes.supelec.fr/ren/rd/scee/theses/ghozzi_2008.html">Des terminaux multi modes aux terminaux intelligents sensibles à leur environnement</a>. Architecture d''un terminal Radio Cognitive (M. GHOZZI)</li><li><a href="http://www.rennes.supelec.fr/ren/rd/scee/theses/khalaf_2013.html">Contributions à l’étude de détection des bandes libres dans le contexte de la radio intelligente</a> (Z. KHALAF)[Pal] Palicot J (Edited by), Radio Enineering: From Software radio to Cognitive Radio, Wiley, August 2011; ISBN: 978-1-84821-296-1</li></ul>', 'Lower Layer', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '144-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-05-10 14:53:03', '2017-05-10 12:53:03', '', 144, 'http://localhost/wordpress/index.php/2017/05/10/144-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
