(795, 1, '2017-05-10 14:54:42', '2017-05-10 12:54:42', '<h3><strong>Mid layer sensors</strong></h3><p><br /> A CR terminal when launched in an environment characterized by heterogeneous and multiple access networks, is neither initially aware of radio access technologies (RAT) which are accessible to it nor of the RAT better suited to its needs and frequency band. The CR terminal also faces situations where approaches such as Dynamic Spectrum Allocation (DSA) and Flexible Spectrum Management (FSM) are adopted by regulators (see Chapter 1, spectrum management). In the latter case, the terminal completely ignores the spectral distribution. Without any a priori information, the terminal needs to scan a significant portion of the spectrum to recognize the existing RAT in its environment and to be able to launch communications. To avoid this search, various solutions have been proposed. Some are based on the use of a common carrier accessible from anywhere like the Cognitive Pilot Channel (CPC), others are based on geo-localization, or on a more futuristic blind spectrum recognition. These three possibilities have been fully described in the chapter 3 of book [Pal]. SCEE team did a lot of work in this area which gave a Blind Standard Recognition Sensor demonstration, which has been demonstrated in many conferences:</p><p><img src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/IntermediateLayer1.png" alt="" width="618" height="489" /></p><p>[Pal] Palicot J (Edited by), Radio Enineering: From Software radio to Cognitive Radio, Wiley, August 2011; ISBN: 978-1-84821-296-1</p>', 'Mid Layer Sensors', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '146-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-05-10 14:54:42', '2017-05-10 12:54:42', '', 146, 'http://localhost/wordpress/index.php/2017/05/10/146-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
